The immediate past President of the Association of National Accountants of Nigeria (ANAN), AlhajiShehu Ladan, has said the association in 2018 fulfilled its obligations to the International Federation of Accountants (IFAC) and the Association of Professional Bodies of Nigeria (APBN). Ladan, who made this known at the 37th Annual General Meeting of the association in Abuja, said the association also fulfilled its obligation to Pan African Federation of Accountants (PAFA), Association of Accounting Bodies in West Africa (ABWA), the International Federation for Accounting Education and Research (IAAER) and Extensible Business Reporting Language (XBRL). According to him, these obligations include the payment of “our membership dues and full active participation in their scheduled programmes. He noted that the association had fully relocated its headquarters to Abuja. Ladan recalled that in 2018, the association commenced the process of relocating the ANAN secretariat from Lagos to Abuja in line with the membership resolution that the AGM of April 30, 2004. He said this was also in keeping with his pronouncement contained in his inaugural address as the president of the association. Ladan said that ANAN did not relent in fostering its relationship with tertiary institutions, adding that the association had commissioned an Accounting Research Centre at Usmanu Danfodiyo University, Sokoto.  ‘ANAN, IFAC bond good for accountancy profession’ ANAN advises FG on alternatives of funding 2015 budget FG needs accountants’ support in corruption fight – ANAN president